06941nam a22009015i 9789633862605DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222018hu     fo  d z      eng d  a2018000793  a9789633862605  a(DE-B1597)633162  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU00aP92.B28bM425 2018 4aP92.B28bM425 2018eb 7aSOC0520002bisacsh04a302.230949622300aMedia Constrained by Context :bInternational Assistance and Democratic Media Transition in the Western Balkans /ced. by Kristina Irion, Tarik Jusić. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Tables -- tList of Figures -- tList of Abbreviations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgements -- tChapter 1: International Assistance and Media Democratization in the Western Balkans: A Theoretical Framework -- tChapter 2: Limited Assistance for Limited Impact—International Media Assistance in Albania -- tChapter 3: Media Reform through Intervention: International Media Assistance in Bosnia and Herzegovina -- tChapter 4: Starting from Scratch: The Role of Media Assistance in the Establishment of Independent Media Institutions in Kosovo -- tChapter 5: Assisting Media Democratization after Low-Intensity Conflict: The Case of Macedonia -- tChapter 6: Media Reforms in Turbulent Times: The Role of Media Assistance in the Establishment of Independent Media Institutions in Serbia -- tChapter 7: Looking for Shortcuts? Assistance to—and Development of—Public Service Broadcasting in Bosnia-Herzegovina, Serbia, Kosovo, Macedonia, and Albania -- tChapter 8: The Uncertain Future: Centers for Investigative Journalism in Bosnia and Herzegovina and Serbia -- tChapter 9: Building Media Systems in the Western Balkans: Lost between Models and Realities -- tChapter 10: Conclusions: A Cross-National Comparison of International Assistance and Media Democratization in the Western Balkans -- tBibliography -- tAbout the Authors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis books draws a comparative balance of twenty years' international media assistance in the five countries of the Western Balkans. The central question was what happens to imported models when they are transposed onto the newly evolving media systems of transitional societies. Albania, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Kosovo, Macedonia and Serbia undertook a range of media reforms to conform with accession requirements of the European Union and the standards of the Council of Europe, among others. The essays explore the nexus between the democratic transformation of the media and international media assistance. The cross-national analysis concludes that the effects of international assistance are highly constrained by the local context. From today's vantage point it becomes obvious, that scaling media assistance does not necessarily improve outcomes. The experiences in the region suggest that imported solutions have not been very cognitive in all aspects of local conditions but international strategies tent to be rather schematic and lacked strategic approaches to promote media policy stability, credible media reform and implementation. The book offers valuable insights into the nature and effects of media assistance and the strategies deployed by international aid agencies, local political forces, media professionals, civil society organizations and other actors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aDemocratizationzBalkan Peninsula. 0aMass media policyzBalkan Peninsula. 0aMass media policy-Balkan Peninsula. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectszBalkan PeninsulaxHistory. 0aMass mediaxSocial aspectszBalkan Peninsul